title: For Sale:  WW2 era Inglis Browning Hi-Power *price drop*
postcontent:
Got this as part of a trade. The collectable nature of this one keeps me from shooting it. I was going to keep it but I keep finding goodies to spend money on. It would be a good addition to a WW2 collection or conversation peice. 

History: The way I understand it, when the Nazis took the FN factory in Belgium, the engineers fled to the UK with the Hi-Power plans. The Nazis like the gun so much they started issuing them to Axis forces. Meanwhile, a Canadian manufacturer (John Inglis & co.) was contracted to make Hi-Powers for allies. These pistol, originally intended for China, were designed with 500meter tangent sight and a shoulder stock that doubles as a holster.

This one is a Mk1* with 80% finish, matching numbers and subtle import marks. Has the cut for the shoulder stock/holster, and small internals appear new. One original magazine and one after market.

title: For Sale:  AMMO COLLECTORS
postcontent:
This is one round of the obsolete and extremely rare 4.25 Liliput ammo.  I included a picture of it next to a 22LR for comparison.  

The 4.25mm Liliput is a centerfire cartridge originally produced in Austria for self-loading pocket pistols made by Erika before World War I. In 1920 the Liliput pistol was designed by August Menz of Suhl to use the cartridge. The cartridge became best known by the Liliput name used on German ammunition after Austria ceased production. The cartridge headspaces on the mouth of the case. It was the smallest centerfire cartridge in production in the 1930s.[1]

title: For Sale:  Benelli Vinci 26" custom paint
location: New Bern/Wilmington, North Carolina, United States
postcontent:
Benelli Vinci. 26" Barrel. Gun is 4 years old this season. Has an estimated 6,000 rounds through it. It's well-used but has been maintained regularly. I usually shoot a case of 3" steel (250 rounds) in duck season and an additional 1,000-1,500 rounds of 2 3/4 clay rounds during sporting clays, skeet and some local 3 gun competitions/yr. Has been cleaned/lubed regularly with Slip2000 (no cheap RemOil crap). 

Gun has had no major failures of any kind. Last year I had to remove some carbon from the magazine tube follower because it was causing the follower to "stick" in the magazine tube. Took some 200 grit sandpaper and scraped the carbon off the follower. Problem fixed. 

The gun was originally finished in Realtree APG. This past summer, I decided to paint the gun rather than pay the $300 to ship/have it dipped in Max-4. I painted off all major parts, took my time and the paint job looks like it was professionally done. I have since done several of my friends guns after they saw mine. The paint has 3 coats of matte acrylic sealer on top of it so it won't flake and chip off as easy. Paint job looks very similar to the Gore Optifade Marsh pattern.

Gun comes with the original Benelli plastic case, manuals, Benelli choke tubes and 2 Patternmaster Code Black tubes (Goose and Improved Cylinder, $80+ each). I use the IC choke on clays, decoying ducks, etc. and save the Goose for diving ducks, geese and other long range shots. 

I'm not terribly motivated to sell this gun. If there's no interest, I'll simply keep using it for the next several seasons. Lowball offers will not be considered. I can email more pictures if needed. This is the only pic I have of the gun with the current camo pattern (blends into the marsh/woods much better than Max-4).
